    <p><strong>A dough sheeter machine is one of the most important pieces of equipment in any commercial bakery.</strong> Whether you are making croissants, puff pastry, pizza bases, chapati, or paratha at scale, a sheeter replaces hours of manual rolling with consistent, uniform sheets of dough in minutes. In India in 2026, dough sheeter prices range from approximately ₹45,000 for a basic table-top manual model to ₹12,00,000 or more for a fully automatic floor-standing reversible sheeter from a European brand. This comprehensive guide covers every type of dough sheeter machine available in India, real pricing, brand comparisons, and practical buying advice so you can make the right investment for your bakery.</p>

    <p>If you are setting up a new bakery or upgrading your production line, understanding the differences between sheeter types, sizes, and mechanisms is critical. A wrong choice means either overspending on capacity you do not need, or buying a machine that cannot keep up with your daily output. We have compiled everything you need to know in one place — from entry-level Indian-made sheeters to premium European machines used in five-star hotel bakeries across India.</p>

    <h2>What Is a Dough Sheeter Machine?</h2>

    <p>A dough sheeter machine (also called a pastry sheeter or dough roller) is a commercial bakery machine that rolls dough into flat, uniform sheets of a specific thickness. It works by passing a lump of dough between two rollers (or a roller and a conveyor belt) repeatedly, gradually reducing the thickness with each pass until the desired sheet thickness is achieved.</p>

    <p>The key advantage over hand-rolling is consistency and speed. A dough sheeter machine produces perfectly even sheets every single time, which is essential for laminated doughs like croissant and puff pastry where uneven thickness causes uneven rise and texture. For high-volume operations producing pizza bases, roti, paratha, or samosa sheets, a sheeter can process in minutes what would take a skilled worker an hour by hand.</p>

    <p>Before investing in a dough sheeter, make sure your broader <a href="/blog/bakery-equipment-list">bakery equipment list</a> is planned out — the sheeter needs to fit into your workflow alongside your <a href="/blog/planetary-mixer-guide">planetary mixer</a> and proving/baking equipment.</p>

    <h2>Types of Dough Sheeter Machines</h2>

    <h3>1. Table-Top Dough Sheeter</h3>
    <p>A compact, portable dough sheeter designed to sit on a worktable or countertop. These are the entry-level option for small bakeries, cafes, and restaurants that need sheeting capability but do not have floor space for a full-size machine.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Belt width:</strong> Typically 450mm to 520mm</li>
      <li><strong>Dough capacity:</strong> Up to 3–5 kg per pass</li>
      <li><strong>Price range:</strong> ₹45,000 – ₹2,50,000 (Indian brands to imported)</li>
      <li><strong>Motor:</strong> 0.25 HP to 0.5 HP</li>
      <li><strong>Weight:</strong> 40–80 kg</li>
      <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Small bakeries, cafes, pizza outlets, home bakery businesses scaling up</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Table-top sheeters are non-reversible — the dough travels in one direction and must be manually repositioned for the next pass. This is slower but perfectly adequate for operations producing up to 50–80 kg of dough daily.</p>

    <h3>2. Floor-Standing Non-Reversible Dough Sheeter</h3>
    <p>A larger, more powerful sheeter mounted on its own stand or legs. Like the table-top version, the dough moves in one direction only, but the larger belt width and more powerful motor allow for higher throughput and handling of stiffer doughs.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Belt width:</strong> 500mm to 600mm</li>
      <li><strong>Dough capacity:</strong> Up to 8–12 kg per pass</li>
      <li><strong>Price range:</strong> ₹1,20,000 – ₹4,50,000</li>
      <li><strong>Motor:</strong> 0.5 HP to 1 HP</li>
      <li><strong>Weight:</strong> 100–200 kg</li>
      <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Medium bakeries, sweet shops, high-volume pizza operations</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>3. Floor-Standing Reversible Dough Sheeter</h3>
    <p>The premium option. A reversible dough sheeter automatically reverses the direction of the conveyor belt, so the dough travels back and forth between the rollers without the operator having to manually reposition it. This dramatically speeds up the sheeting process and reduces operator fatigue.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Belt width:</strong> 500mm to 700mm (some models up to 800mm)</li>
      <li><strong>Dough capacity:</strong> Up to 15–25 kg per pass</li>
      <li><strong>Price range:</strong> ₹3,00,000 – ₹12,00,000+</li>
      <li><strong>Motor:</strong> 1 HP to 2 HP</li>
      <li><strong>Weight:</strong> 250–500 kg</li>
      <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Large commercial bakeries, hotel bakeries, croissant production, industrial puff pastry lines</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Reversible sheeters are essential for laminated doughs (croissant, Danish, puff pastry) where the dough needs many passes at progressively thinner settings. A reversible machine can complete 20–30 passes in a few minutes, whereas a non-reversible model would take significantly longer with manual repositioning each time.</p>

    <h3>4. Fully Automatic / Programmable Dough Sheeter</h3>
    <p>Top-end machines with programmable thickness settings, automatic gap adjustment, and in some cases integrated cutting and folding stations. These are used in industrial bakeries and large-scale production facilities.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Belt width:</strong> 600mm to 800mm+</li>
      <li><strong>Price range:</strong> ₹8,00,000 – ₹15,00,000+</li>
      <li><strong>Best for:</strong> Industrial bakeries, frozen dough manufacturers, large hotel chains</li>
    </ul>

