    <p><strong>Our recommendation:</strong> For most Indian bakeries producing a mix of products (puff pastry, pizza, cookies, roti), a 500mm or 520mm model offers the best balance of versatility and value. If croissant production is a core product, go with 600mm minimum to handle the wider dough blocks needed for proper lamination.</p>

    <h2>Dough Sheeter Machine Applications</h2>

    <h3>Puff Pastry Production</h3>
    <p>Puff pastry requires the dough to be sheeted and folded multiple times to create dozens of thin layers of dough separated by butter. A reversible dough sheeter is almost mandatory for serious puff pastry production. The machine must handle cold, stiff dough with butter layers without tearing or smearing the butter. Look for models with precise thickness adjustment (down to 1mm increments) and a powerful motor that does not strain under stiff laminated dough.</p>

    <h3>Croissant Production</h3>
    <p>Similar to puff pastry, croissant dough is a laminated dough requiring multiple sheeting and folding passes. A good dough sheeter machine is arguably the single most important piece of equipment for a croissant bakery in India. The sheeter must maintain the dough at a cool temperature — some premium models have chilled rollers for this purpose. For a dedicated croissant operation in India, a 600mm reversible sheeter from a brand like Ferneto or Rondo is the standard choice, though Sinmag offers excellent value at a lower price point.</p>

    <h3>Pizza Dough</h3>
    <p>For pizza outlets and restaurants producing large volumes of pizza bases, a dough sheeter replaces hand-stretching and ensures consistent base thickness across every pizza. A 450mm or 500mm table-top sheeter is usually sufficient for most pizza operations. Some pizzerias prefer a dedicated pizza dough press (a different machine), but a sheeter offers more versatility since it can handle other products too.</p>

    <h3>Roti, Chapati, and Paratha</h3>
    <p>Many Indian sweet shops, restaurants, and catering operations use dough sheeters to roll out roti, chapati, naan, and paratha dough at scale. While dedicated <a href="/blog/roti-making-machine">roti making machines</a> exist for fully automated production, a dough sheeter is more versatile — you can use the same machine for pastry work, samosa sheets, and flatbreads.</p>

    <h3>Cookies, Biscuits, and Fondant</h3>
    <p>Dough sheeters are also used for rolling cookie dough to uniform thickness before cutting, rolling fondant for cake decoration, and producing other flat dough products like crackers and savoury snacks.</p>

