    <h2>Manual vs Semi-Automatic vs Fully Automatic Dough Sheeters</h2>

    <p>Understanding the automation level is crucial for matching the right dough sheeter machine to your production needs and budget.</p>

    <h3>Manual Dough Sheeter</h3>
    <p>In a manual dough sheeter, the operator adjusts the roller gap by hand (using a wheel or lever) and feeds the dough manually. The conveyor belt is motor-driven, but all other operations are manual. This is the most affordable option and is suitable for small bakeries where sheeting volumes are low and the operator has time to manage the machine between other tasks.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Pros:</strong> Low cost, simple operation, minimal maintenance, easy to clean</li>
      <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Slower output, requires attentive operator, thickness consistency depends on operator skill</li>
      <li><strong>Price:</strong> ₹45,000 – ₹1,50,000</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Semi-Automatic Dough Sheeter</h3>
    <p>Semi-automatic models feature motorised roller gap adjustment (press a button to change thickness) and, in reversible models, automatic belt direction reversal. The operator still feeds the dough and monitors the process, but the machine handles the mechanical adjustments. This is the sweet spot for most medium-sized Indian bakeries.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Pros:</strong> Faster operation, more consistent results, less operator fatigue</li>
      <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Higher cost, more complex maintenance</li>
      <li><strong>Price:</strong> ₹1,50,000 – ₹6,00,000</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Fully Automatic / Programmable Dough Sheeter</h3>
    <p>Fully automatic sheeters allow the operator to program the entire sheeting sequence — number of passes, thickness reduction per pass, final thickness, and belt speed. The operator places the dough block, presses start, and the machine completes the entire process automatically. Some models include integrated flour dusting, cutting, and folding attachments.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Pros:</strong> Maximum consistency, highest throughput, minimal operator skill required, programmable recipes</li>
      <li><strong>Cons:</strong> Very expensive, complex maintenance, requires trained technician for service</li>
      <li><strong>Price:</strong> ₹6,00,000 – ₹15,00,000+</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Motor Power and Speed Specifications</h2>

    <p>The motor is the heart of a dough sheeter machine. An underpowered motor will struggle with stiff doughs (especially cold laminated doughs with butter), overheat during extended use, and wear out prematurely. Here is what to look for.</p>

    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Sheeter Type</th><th>Recommended Motor Power</th><th>Belt Speed</th><th>Suitable Dough Types</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Table-top 450mm</td><td>0.25 – 0.37 HP</td><td>3–5 m/min</td><td>Soft doughs, pizza, roti</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Table-top 500–520mm</td><td>0.37 – 0.5 HP</td><td>4–6 m/min</td><td>Soft to medium doughs, basic pastry</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Floor non-reversible 500–600mm</td><td>0.5 – 1 HP</td><td>5–8 m/min</td><td>All dough types including stiff doughs</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Floor reversible 500–600mm</td><td>1 – 1.5 HP</td><td>6–12 m/min</td><td>All types including cold laminated dough</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Floor reversible 600mm+</td><td>1.5 – 2 HP</td><td>8–15 m/min</td><td>Heavy laminated doughs, industrial use</td></tr>
