    <h2>Maintenance and Cleaning Guide for Dough Sheeters</h2>

    <p>Proper maintenance is essential to keep your dough sheeter running smoothly and to maximise its lifespan. A well-maintained sheeter can last 10–15 years; a neglected one may fail within 2–3 years.</p>

    <h3>Daily Cleaning Routine</h3>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Scrape off dough residue:</strong> Use a plastic dough scraper (never metal) to remove all dough stuck to the belt, rollers, and side guides after each production run.</li>
      <li><strong>Brush the belt:</strong> Use a soft nylon brush to remove flour and dried dough particles from the conveyor belt surface.</li>
      <li><strong>Wipe rollers:</strong> Wipe the rollers with a damp cloth. For sticky residue, use a food-safe degreaser spray and wipe clean.</li>
      <li><strong>Clean the flour duster:</strong> If your sheeter has an integrated flour duster, empty and clean the flour container daily to prevent moisture absorption and caking.</li>
      <li><strong>Clean the crumb tray:</strong> Remove and empty the crumb/flour collection tray underneath the machine.</li>
      <li><strong>Wipe the exterior:</strong> Wipe down all stainless steel surfaces with a damp cloth.</li>
    </ol>

    <h3>Weekly Maintenance</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Check belt tension — the belt should be taut but not over-tight. Adjust using the tension screws if the belt is sagging or tracking to one side.</li>
      <li>Inspect the belt surface for cuts, tears, or excessive wear. A damaged belt affects sheet quality and should be replaced promptly.</li>
      <li>Lubricate the roller bearings and any moving parts according to the manufacturer's guide (food-grade lubricant only).</li>
      <li>Check the thickness adjustment mechanism — it should move smoothly without sticking or play.</li>
      <li>Inspect all electrical connections, switches, and safety interlocks.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Monthly / Quarterly Maintenance</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Deep clean the belt by removing it from the machine (if your model allows) and washing it with warm water and mild detergent. Allow it to dry completely before reinstalling.</li>
      <li>Check motor operation — listen for unusual sounds (grinding, humming, clicking) which may indicate bearing wear.</li>
      <li>Inspect the power cable and plug for damage.</li>
      <li>Tighten all nuts, bolts, and fasteners.</li>
      <li>Schedule a professional service visit if included in your warranty or service contract.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Common Dough Sheeter Problems and Solutions</h3>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Problem</th><th>Likely Cause</th><th>Solution</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Dough sticks to belt</td><td>Insufficient flour dusting, worn belt surface</td><td>Dust more flour, replace belt if worn smooth</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Uneven sheet thickness</td><td>Roller gap misaligned, worn roller surface</td><td>Recalibrate roller gap, check rollers for damage</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Belt tracking to one side</td><td>Uneven belt tension</td><td>Adjust tension screws on the side the belt is moving toward</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Motor overheating</td><td>Overloading with too much or too stiff dough</td><td>Reduce dough load per pass, check motor ventilation</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Unusual noise during operation</td><td>Worn bearings, loose fasteners</td><td>Lubricate bearings, tighten all fasteners, call service if noise persists</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Dough tears during sheeting</td><td>Speed too fast, thickness reduction too aggressive</td><td>Slow down belt speed, reduce thickness in smaller increments per pass</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Space Requirements and Installation</h2>

    <p>Proper installation of your dough sheeter machine is essential for safe operation and optimal performance. Here are the key considerations.</p>

    <h3>Floor Requirements</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Level surface:</strong> The machine must sit on a perfectly level floor. An uneven surface causes vibration, belt tracking issues, and uneven dough thickness. Use a spirit level to check.</li>
      <li><strong>Floor strength:</strong> Floor-standing reversible sheeters weigh 250–500 kg. Ensure your floor can handle the load, especially on upper stories.</li>
      <li><strong>Non-slip surface:</strong> The floor around the sheeter should be non-slip, as flour dust accumulation creates a slip hazard.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Electrical Requirements</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Table-top models:</strong> Single-phase 220V, 15A socket (standard power socket is usually sufficient)</li>
      <li><strong>Floor non-reversible:</strong> Single-phase 220V, 15A or 32A dedicated socket depending on motor size</li>
      <li><strong>Floor reversible:</strong> Three-phase 440V supply required for most models above 1 HP. Needs dedicated MCB and proper earthing.</li>
      <li><strong>Always install an ELCB (Earth Leakage Circuit Breaker)</strong> on the circuit feeding the sheeter for safety.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Ventilation and Temperature</h3>
    <p>Dough sheeters work best in a cool environment, especially when processing laminated doughs. The ideal ambient temperature for croissant and puff pastry production is 18–22 degrees Celsius. If your bakery production area is warmer (as is common in most Indian cities), consider positioning the sheeter near your air conditioning unit or investing in a dedicated cooling system for the sheeting area.</p>

    <p>Ensure at least 15cm clearance around the motor housing for air circulation to prevent overheating.</p>

